  doi = {10.1080/13504509.2014.965238},
  abstract = {The consumption of food is associated with significant environmental$\backslash$nimpacts, and the disposable incomes of individuals and households play$\backslash$nan important role in what food is consumed. It may be assumed that the$\backslash$nhigher the income, the more food consumed. However, it may also be$\backslash$nsupposed that people with higher incomes are more likely to lead$\backslash$nhealthier lifestyles and therefore consume more moderately.$\backslash$nThis analysis is based on food consumption data from the Household$\backslash$nbudget and living conditions survey of the Hungarian Central Statistical$\backslash$nOffice, combined with the latest database from the Global Footprint$\backslash$nNetwork. Results show that a higher level of consumption is able to$\backslash$noffset a healthier consumption structure. For the upper three income$\backslash$ndeciles ecological footprints for food consumption are not notably$\backslash$nhigher, as the individuals in these groups use their higher incomes to$\backslash$npurchase and consume more fruit and vegetables. A scenario analysis is$\backslash$ncarried out along the income deciles to illustrate the changes needed to$\backslash$nmove towards a healthier food consumption structure. Results highlight$\backslash$nthat the ecological footprint of food consumption is not equally$\backslash$ndistributed among the income groups, and that middle-upper level income$\backslash$ngroups have a greater responsibility to decrease their food consumption.$\backslash$nThe footprints of this group would be decreased to a greater extent by$\backslash$nconsuming healthier diets than they would with lower income deciles.$\backslash$nPolicy measures that are employed to reduce the ecological footprint$\backslash$nshould take into account the responsibility of the different$\backslash$nsocio-economic levels. Correspondingly, identifying and targeting social$\backslash$ngroups by income level may be a suitable approach for better$\backslash$ncommunicating about sustainable consumption.},
